    <div class="section">
      

<div id="review_27350854" class="review" itemprop="reviews" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Review">
  <link itemprop="url" href="https://www.goodreads.com/review/show/27350854" />
    <a title="Melissa McShane" class="left imgcol" href="/user/show/1329059-melissa-mcshane"><img alt="Melissa McShane" src="https://images.gr-assets.com/users/1216147749p2/1329059.jpg" /></a>

  <div class="left bodycol">
    <div class="reviewHeader uitext stacked">
        <a class="reviewDate createdAt right" href="/review/show/27350854?book_show_action=true">Jul 15, 2008</a>

      <span itemprop="author" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Person">
        <a title="Melissa McShane" class="user" itemprop="url" name="Melissa McShane" href="/user/show/1329059-melissa-mcshane">Melissa McShane</a>
      </span>

        rated it
        <span class=" staticStars notranslate" title="really liked it"><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10">really liked it</span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p0"></span></span>

          <span class="greyText">&nbsp;&middot;&nbsp;</span>
          <a class="lightGreyText" title="Paperback 9780553375626" href="/book/show/1206542.Bellwether">review of another edition</a>


        

          <div class="uitext greyText bookshelves">
            Shelves:
              <a class="actionLinkLite" href="/review/list/1329059-melissa-mcshane?shelf=science-fiction">science-fiction</a>, 
              <a class="actionLinkLite" href="/review/list/1329059-melissa-mcshane?shelf=own">own</a>, 
              <a class="actionLinkLite" href="/review/list/1329059-melissa-mcshane?shelf=contemporary-fiction">contemporary-fiction</a>, 
              <a class="actionLinkLite" href="/review/list/1329059-melissa-mcshane?shelf=romance">romance</a>
          </div>
    </div>


        <div class="reviewText stacked">
              <span id="reviewTextContainer27350854" class="readable"
              >
            
<span id="freeTextContainer11331370074838426168">Like a lot of people, I&apos;ve needed lighter reading these past few months, and when I discovered the audiobook I was listening to was (though brilliant) too heavy-going, I switched to an old favorite. This is not technically science fiction or fantasy, but it&apos;s a book about science, and research, and trends, and I&apos;ve always enjoyed the way Willis manages to tell a complex story in a way that hides its complexity.<br/><br/>I&apos;m dropping my rating a star this time, though, because despite still enjoying it tho</span>
  <span id="freeText11331370074838426168" style="display:none">Like a lot of people, I've needed lighter reading these past few months, and when I discovered the audiobook I was listening to was (though brilliant) too heavy-going, I switched to an old favorite. This is not technically science fiction or fantasy, but it's a book about science, and research, and trends, and I've always enjoyed the way Willis manages to tell a complex story in a way that hides its complexity.<br /><br />I'm dropping my rating a star this time, though, because despite still enjoying it thoroughly--and the narrator Kate Reading is very good and sounds a little like Kathleen Turner in <i>Undercover Blues</i>, always a plus--I was struck by how judgmental the main character is in certain ways that undermine the message of the story. Sandra is a scientist studying fads, and a major part of the novel is showing how easy it is to fall for certain fads, like shunning people who have a difference it's acceptable to mock, or changing one's food preferences for the next big thing. So there's a lot of talk about fads, both within the story and as examples from history. But Sandra is subject to her own fads, and she doesn't seem to be aware of that. <br /><br />For example: One of Willis's writing techniques is to use minor characters as a kind of synecdoche, making them stand for the whole of, not a group, but an abstract idea. Here, for example, Sandra encounters a lot of waiters who are all of a type: young, not very well educated, trendy, and unaware of the existence of other possible ways of thinking. Willis does this not because to mock stupid young people, but as an example of a trend in thought (or actually a trend she perceived in 1996, when the book was written). And it works fine that way so long as you think of those characters not as people, but as representatives of a concept. But from another perspective, these encounters reveal Sandra to be as judgmental as they are, because she is universally dismissive of them. But since she has the "right" opinions, it's okay for her to judge.<br /><br />This struck me particularly in Sandra's library visits. She makes a point of checking out classics because of the library's policy (which she abhors) of discarding books that haven't been used in over a year. (Side note: I used to work in a library, and this is a good policy. Just sayin'.) The implication is that these are the "good" books, and books like <i>The Bridges of Madison County</i> (wow, how old IS this book?) are trash. But this is just another way of imposing one person's literary values on a community. Sandra may love the classics she's checking out, but she's not doing it because it's what she wants to read, she's doing it as a way of making sure the "right" values are transmitted. Again, there's the implication that this is okay because the reader of <i>Bellwether</i> naturally shares Sandra's opinions. But <i>Bellwether</i> is nominally science fiction, which is itself a genre that's been considered trashy and not of value to the ages! So this opinion expressed in a science fiction book comes across as questionable.<br /><br />Despite these reservations, I still love this book. I like the characters, even the annoying Flip, whose sloppiness about her job drives me nuts. The romance is understated, but sweet. And if you do happen to agree with the slant of the narrative opinion, it's satisfying in a "other people feel this too" way, like the throwaway scene where a man tries to get a clueless clerk to give him the right change. I'd consider this one of Willis's lesser novels, like <a href="https://www.goodreads.com/book/show/24982.Uncharted_Territory" title="Uncharted Territory by Connie Willis" rel="nofollow noopener">Uncharted Territory</a>, which still makes it worth reading.</span>
  <a data-text-id="11331370074838426168" href="#" onclick="swapContent($(this));; return false;">...more</a>

          </span>
        </div>


